Chat Edit: 'The error message you're encountering is related to a permissions issue when RawrZ tries to access the Recycle Bin directory (D:\$RECYCLE.BIN\S-1-5-18). This is a common problem on Windows systems because certain directories are protected by the operating system, and unprivileged users cannot read from them.

Here are some steps you can take to troubleshoot and resolve this issue:

1. Run as Administrator
Try running Visual Studio Code (VS Code) or any other application that hosts RawrZ as an administrator. Right-click on the VS Code icon and select "Run as administrator". This should give your user account elevated privileges, allowing it to access protected directories.

2. Exclude Recycle Bin from Scanning
If you're running a script that scans the entire file system, you can exclude the Recycle Bin directory from the scan. For example, in Node.js, you can use a conditional check to skip scanning the Recycle Bin:

const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

function safeReaddir(dirPath) {
  if (dirPath.includes('$RECYCLE.BIN')) return [];
  try {
    return fs.readdirSync(dirPath);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(`Failed to read directory ${dirPath}:`, err);
    return [];
  }
}

const directories = safeReaddir('D:\\');
console.log(directories);
3. Disable Recycle Bin Folder
If you're running a script that needs to scan the entire file system, consider disabling the Recycle Bin folder on your system. This can be done by moving it to another location or renaming it.

4. Modify the Extension Code
If you have control over the extension code, you can modify it to handle the EPERM error gracefully. For example, you can catch the error and log a message instead of throwing an exception:

const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

function safeReaddir(dirPath) {
  try {
    return fs.readdirSync(dirPath);
  } catch (err) {
    if (err.code === 'EPERM' && dirPath.includes('$RECYCLE.BIN')) {
      console.warn(`Permission denied when accessing ${dirPath}`);
      return [];
    }
    throw err;
  }
}

const directories = safeReaddir('D:\\');
console.log(directories);
5. Check VS Code Settings
If you're using Visual Studio Code, ensure that your settings are not excluding or ignoring the Recycle Bin directory. You can check the files.exclude and search.exclude settings in the VS Code settings (File > Preferences > Settings).

6. Update RawrZ
Ensure that you are using the latest version of RawrZ. Sometimes, issues like this are resolved in newer versions.

7. Reach Out for Support
If none of the above steps work, consider reaching out to the support team or community for RawrZ. Provide them with the error message and any relevant details so they can assist you better.

By following these steps, you should be able to resolve the permissions issue that is causing RawrZ to fail when accessing protected directories on your Windows system.'
